# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elliptic-curve-cryptography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In cryptography, **Curve25519** is an elliptic curve used in elliptic-curve cryptography (ECC) offering 128 bits of security (256-bit key size) and designed for use with the Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman (ECDH) key agreement scheme, first described and implemented by Daniel J.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] It is one of the fastest curves in ECC, and is not covered by any known patents.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The reference implementation is public domain software.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The original Curve25519 paper defined it as a Diffie–Hellman (DH) function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Bernstein has since proposed that the name Curve25519 be used for the underlying curve, and the name **X25519** for the DH function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The curve used is $y^{2}=x^{3}+486662x^{2}+x$ , a Montgomery curve, over the prime field defined by the pseudo-Mersenne prime number $2^{255}-19$ (hence the numeric "25519" in the name), and it uses the base point $x=9$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] This subgroup has a co-factor of 8, meaning the number of elements in the subgroup is ⁠1/8⁠ that of the elliptic curve group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Using a prime order subgroup prevents mounting a Pohlig–Hellman algorithm attack.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The protocol uses compressed elliptic point (only *X* coordinates), so it allows efficient use of the Montgomery ladder for ECDH, using only *XZ* coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Curve25519 is constructed such that it avoids many potential implementation pitfalls.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The curve is birationally equivalent to a twisted Edwards curve used in the Ed25519 signature scheme.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In 2005, Curve25519 was first released by Daniel J.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In 2013, interest began to increase considerably when it was discovered that the NSA had potentially implemented a backdoor into the P-256 curve based Dual_EC_DRBG algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] While not directly related, suspicious aspects of the NIST's P curve constants led to concerns that the NSA had chosen values that gave them an advantage in breaking the encryption.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Since 2013, Curve25519 has become the *de facto* alternative to P-256, being used in a wide variety of applications.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Starting in 2014, OpenSSH defaults to Curve25519-based ECDH and GnuPG adds support for Ed25519 keys for signing and encryption.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The use of the curve was eventually standardized for both key exchange and signature in 2020.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In 2017, NIST announced that Curve25519 and Curve448 would be added to Special Publication 800-186, which specifies approved elliptic curves for use by the US Federal Government.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] A 2019 draft of "FIPS 186-5" notes the intention to allow usage of Ed25519 for digital signatures.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] The 2023 update of Special Publication 800-186 allows usage of Curve25519.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In February 2017, the DNSSEC specification for using Ed25519 and Ed448 was published as RFC 8080, assigning algorithm numbers 15 and 16.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] In 2018, DKIM specification was amended so as to allow signatures with this algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/curve25519] Also in 2018, RFC 8446 was published as the new Transport Layer Security v1.3 standard.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In mathematics, for given real numbers a and b , the logarithm $\log _{b}(a)$ is a number x such that $b^{x}=a$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm is an analogous concept in group theory.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In any group G , powers $b^{k}$ can be defined for all integers k , and the **discrete logarithm** $\log _{b}(a)$ is an integer k such that $b^{k}=a$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In the special case of arithmetic modulo an integer m , the more commonly used term is **index**: One can write $k=\mathrm {ind} _{b}a\!\!\!\!{\pmod {m}}$ when $b^{k}\equiv a\!\!\!\!{\pmod {m}}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Discrete logarithms are quickly computable in a few special cases, but no efficient method is known for computing them in general.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Several cryptographic systems, including Diffie–Hellman and ElGamal, base their security on the hardness assumption that the discrete logarithm problem over carefully chosen groups has no efficient solution.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In general, there is no subexponential time solution for black box groups.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Denote its group operation by multiplication and its identity element by 1 .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Similarly, let $b^{-k}$ denote the product of $b^{-1}$ with itself k times.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For $k=0$ , the k th power is the identity: $b^{0}=1$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] An integer k that solves the equation $b^{k}=a$ is termed a **discrete logarithm** (or simply **logarithm**, in this context) of a to the base b .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For any number a in this list, one can compute $\log _{10}a$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] These are instances of the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Other base-10 logarithms in the real numbers are not instances of the discrete logarithm problem, because they involve non-integer exponents.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] While integer exponents can be defined in any group using products and inverses, arbitrary real exponents, such as this 1.724276…, require other concepts such as the exponential function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In group-theoretic terms, the powers of 10 form a cyclic group G under multiplication, and 10 is a generator for this group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm $\log _{10}a$ is defined for any a in G .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] A similar example holds for any non-zero real number b .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For any element a of G , one can compute $\log _{b}a$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] One of the simplest settings for discrete logarithms is the group **Z***p*×.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] This is the group of multiplication modulo the prime p .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Its elements are non-zero congruence classes modulo p , and the group product of two elements may be obtained by ordinary integer multiplication of the elements followed by reduction modulo p .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The k th power of one of the numbers in this group may be computed by finding its ' k th power as an integer and then finding the remainder after division by p .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] When the numbers involved are large, it is more efficient to reduce modulo p multiple times during the computation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Regardless of the specific algorithm used, this operation is called modular exponentiation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm is just the inverse operation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For example, consider the equation $3^{k}\equiv 13{\pmod {17}}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] From the example above, one solution is $k=4$ , but it is not the only solution.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Hence the equation has infinitely many solutions of the form $4+16n$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Moreover, because $16$ is the smallest positive integer m satisfying $3^{m}\equiv 1{\pmod {17}}$ , these are the only solutions.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Equivalently, the set of all possible solutions can be expressed by the constraint that $k\equiv 4{\pmod {16}}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In the special case where b is the identity element 1 of the group G , the discrete logarithm $\log _{b}a$ is undefined for a other than 1 , and every integer k is a discrete logarithm for $a=1$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Let *C* be a Weierstrass normal form elliptic curve in the projective plane over a field *F*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Let *O* be the point at infinity on *C*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For any points *P* and *Q* of *C*, let *P* # *Q* denote the unique third point of *C*, where the line through *P* and *Q* intersects *C*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] (If *P* = *Q*, then the line in question is the line tangent to *C* at *P*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] If *P* = *Q* = *O*, then *P* # *Q* = *O*.) Define an "addition" operation on *C* by $P+Q=(P\;\#\;Q)\;\#\;O.$ This addition operation makes *C* a commutative group with identity element *O*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For any point *P* of *C*, let $kP=P+P+\cdots +P$ denote the sum of *k* copies of *P*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In this context, the discrete logarithm problem is: Given points *P* and *Q*, find *k* such that $Q=kP$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] When the underlying field *F* is a finite field, this problem has cryptographic applications.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Powers obey the usual algebraic identity $b^{k+l}=b^{k}\cdot b^{l}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] defined by $f(k)=b^{k}$ is a group homomorphism from the group of integers $\mathbf {Z}$ under addition onto the subgroup H of G generated by b .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Conversely, $\log _{b}a$ does not exist for a that are not in H .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] where $\mathbf {Z} _{n}$ denotes the additive group of integers modulo n .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Can the discrete logarithm be computed in polynomial time on a classical computer?
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm problem is considered to be computationally intractable.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For a classical (e.g., non-quantum) computer, no efficient (polynomial-time) algorithm is yet known for computing discrete logarithms in general.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] A general algorithm for computing $\log _{b}a$ in finite groups G is to raise b to larger and larger powers k until the desired a is found.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] This algorithm is sometimes called *trial multiplication*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] It requires running time linear in the size of the group G and thus exponential in the number of digits in the size of the group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Therefore, it is an exponential-time algorithm, practical only for small groups G .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] More sophisticated algorithms exist, usually inspired by similar algorithms for integer factorization.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] These algorithms run faster than the naïve algorithm, some of them proportional to the square root of the size of the group, and thus exponential in half the number of digits in the size of the group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] However, none of them runs in polynomial time (in the number of digits in the size of the group).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] There is an efficient quantum algorithm due to Peter Shor.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Efficient classical algorithms also exist in certain special cases.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] For example, in the group of the integers modulo p under addition, the power $b^{k}$ becomes a product $b\cdot k$ , and equality means congruence modulo p in the integers.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The extended Euclidean algorithm finds k quickly.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] With Diffie–Hellman, a cyclic group modulo a prime p is used, allowing an efficient computation of the discrete logarithm with Pohlig–Hellman if the order of the group (being $p-1$ ) is sufficiently smooth, i.e. has no large prime factors.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] There exist groups for which computing discrete logarithms is apparently difficult.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] In some cases (e.g. large prime order subgroups of groups $\mathbf {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ ) there is not only no efficient algorithm known for the worst case, but the average-case complexity can be shown to be about as hard as the worst case using random self-reducibility.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] At the same time, the inverse problem of discrete exponentiation is not difficult (it can be computed efficiently using exponentiation by squaring, for example).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] This asymmetry is analogous to the one between integer factorization and integer multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Both asymmetries (and other possibly one-way functions) have been exploited in the construction of cryptographic systems.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] Popular choices for the group G in discrete logarithm cryptography (DLC) are the cyclic groups $\mathbf {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ (e.g.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] ElGamal encryption, Diffie–Hellman key exchange, and the Digital Signature Algorithm) and cyclic subgroups of elliptic curves over finite fields (*see* Elliptic curve cryptography).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] While there is no publicly known algorithm for solving the discrete logarithm problem in general, the first three steps of the number field sieve algorithm only depend on the group G , not on the specific elements of G whose finite $\log$ is desired.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] By precomputing these three steps for a specific group, one need only carry out the last step, which is much less computationally expensive than the first three, to obtain a specific logarithm in that group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] It turns out that much internet traffic uses one of a handful of groups that are of order 1024 bits or less, e.g. cyclic groups with order of the Oakley primes specified in RFC 2409.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The Logjam attack used this vulnerability to compromise a variety of internet services that allowed the use of groups whose order was a 512-bit prime number, so called export grade.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The authors of the Logjam attack estimate that the much more difficult precomputation needed to solve the discrete log problem for a 1024-bit prime would be within the budget of a large national intelligence agency such as the U.S.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/discrete-logarithm] The Logjam authors speculate that precomputation against widely reused 1024 DH primes is behind claims in leaked NSA documents that NSA is able to break much of current cryptography.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Elliptic curves are applicable for key agreement, digital signatures, pseudo-random generators and other tasks.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Indirectly, they can be used for encryption by combining the key agreement with a symmetric encryption scheme.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] They are also used in several integer factorization algorithms that have applications in cryptography, such as Lenstra elliptic-curve factorization.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The use of elliptic curves in cryptography was suggested independently by Neal Koblitz and Victor S.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Elliptic curve cryptography algorithms entered wide use starting in 2004.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NIST recommended fifteen elliptic curves for use in the Digital Signature Standard.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] These curves were later specified in FIPS 186-4, which was superseded by FIPS 186-5 in 2023 and withdrawn in 2024.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NIST moved its recommended elliptic-curve domain parameters to Special Publication 800-186.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] SP 800-186 includes previously recommended Weierstrass curves and two Edwards curves for EdDSA; it also deprecates binary-field curves and strongly recommends use of prime curves.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] At the RSA Conference 2005, the National Security Agency (NSA) announced Suite B, which used ECC for digital signature generation and key exchange.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Suite B was later superseded by the Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite (CNSA), and NSA announced CNSA 2.0 as a quantum-resistant transition suite for national security systems.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Since the early 2000s, cryptographic primitives based on bilinear mappings on various elliptic curve groups, such as the Weil and Tate pairings, have been studied.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Schemes based on these primitives include identity-based encryption as well as pairing-based signatures, signcryption, key agreement, and proxy re-encryption.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Elliptic curve cryptography is used successfully in numerous popular protocols, such as Transport Layer Security and Bitcoin.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In 2013, *The New York Times* stated that Dual Elliptic Curve Deterministic Random Bit Generation (or Dual_EC_DRBG) had been included as a NIST national standard due to the influence of NSA, which had included a deliberate weakness in the algorithm and the recommended elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] RSA Security in September 2013 issued an advisory recommending that its customers discontinue using any software based on Dual_EC_DRBG.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In the wake of the exposure of Dual_EC_DRBG as "an NSA undercover operation", cryptography experts have also expressed concern over the security of the NIST recommended elliptic curves, suggesting a return to encryption based on non-elliptic-curve groups.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Additionally, in August 2015, the NSA announced that it planned to replace Suite B with a new cipher suite due to concerns about quantum computing attacks on ECC.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NSA later published CNSA 2.0 guidance for a transition to quantum-resistant algorithms for national security systems.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] While the RSA patent expired in 2000, there may be patents in force covering certain aspects of ECC technology, including at least one ECC scheme (ECMQV).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Bernstein have argued that the US government elliptic curve digital signature standard (ECDSA; NIST FIPS 186-3) and certain practical ECC-based key exchange schemes (including ECDH) can be implemented without infringing those patents.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For the purposes of this article, an *elliptic curve* is a plane curve over a finite field (rather than the real numbers).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] along with a distinguished point at infinity, denoted ∞.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Curves over fields of characteristic 2 or 3, and curves used in other representations such as Montgomery or Edwards form, are written differently.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] This set of points, together with the group operation of elliptic curves, is an abelian group, with the point at infinity as an identity element.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Public-key cryptography is based on the intractability of certain mathematical problems.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Early public-key systems, such as RSA's 1983 patent, based their security on the assumption that it is difficult to factor a large integer composed of two or more large prime factors which are far apart.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For elliptic-curve protocols, a central hardness assumption is the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP): given a public base point P and another point $Q=kP$ , it should be infeasible to recover k .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Key-agreement protocols such as ECDH rely on related Diffie–Hellman assumptions, such as the difficulty of computing $abP$ from P , $aP$ , and $bP$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The security of elliptic curve cryptography depends on the ability to compute point multiplication efficiently and the apparent inability to reverse it for properly chosen curves and key sizes.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The size and structure of the curve group, rather than only the total number of coordinate pairs satisfying the curve equation, determine the difficulty of the problem.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The primary benefit promised by elliptic curve cryptography over alternatives such as RSA is a smaller key size, reducing storage and transmission requirements.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For example, a 256-bit elliptic curve public key should provide comparable security to a 3072-bit RSA public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] To use ECC, all parties must agree on all the elements defining the elliptic curve, that is, the *domain parameters* of the scheme.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The underlying finite field is typically either a prime field, denoted $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ , or a binary field, denoted $\mathbb {F} _{2^{m}}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In the binary case, m and an irreducible reduction polynomial f specify the field representation; f is not an auxiliary curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The elliptic curve is defined by the coefficients in its defining equation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Finally, the cyclic subgroup is defined by its generator (a.k.a.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For cryptographic application, the order of *G*, that is the smallest positive number *n* such that $nG={\mathcal {O}}$ (the point at infinity of the curve, and the identity element), is normally prime.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Since *n* is the size of a subgroup of $E(\mathbb {F} _{q})$ , it follows from Lagrange's theorem that the number $h={\frac {1}{n}}|E(\mathbb {F} _{q})|$ is an integer.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In cryptographic applications, this number *h*, called the *cofactor*, is usually small, ideally 1.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Protocols using curves with cofactors greater than 1 must handle the cofactor appropriately.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] To summarize: in the prime case, the domain parameters are $(p,a,b,G,n,h)$ ; in the binary case, they are $(m,f,a,b,G,n,h)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Unless there is an assurance that domain parameters were generated by a party trusted with respect to their use, the domain parameters *must* be validated before use.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The generation of domain parameters is not usually done by each participant because this involves computing the number of points on a curve which is time-consuming and troublesome to implement.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] As a result, several standard bodies published domain parameters of elliptic curves for several common field sizes.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NIST has approved many SECG curves, so there is a significant overlap between the specifications published by NIST and SECG.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] EC domain parameters may be specified either by value or by name.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Because all the fastest known algorithms that allow one to solve the ECDLP (baby-step giant-step, Pollard's rho, etc.), need $O({\sqrt {n}})$ steps, it follows that the size of the underlying field should be roughly twice the security parameter.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For example, for 128-bit security one needs a curve over $\mathbb {F} _{q}$ , where $q\approx 2^{256}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] This can be contrasted with finite-field cryptography (e.g., DSA) which requires 3072-bit public keys and 256-bit private keys, and integer factorization cryptography (e.g., RSA) which requires a 3072-bit value of *n*, where the private key should be just as large.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] However, the public key may be smaller to accommodate efficient encryption, especially when processing power is limited.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Historic public ECDLP challenge records include a 112-bit key for the prime field case and a 109-bit key for the binary field case.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For the prime field case, this was broken in July 2009 using a cluster of over 200 PlayStation 3 game consoles and could have been finished in 3.5 months using this cluster when running continuously.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The binary field case was broken in April 2004 using 2600 computers over 17 months.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The binary-field ECC2K-130 challenge has also been targeted by distributed computation using CPUs, GPUs, and FPGAs.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] A close examination of the addition rules shows that in order to add two points, one needs not only several additions and multiplications in $\mathbb {F} _{q}$ but also an inversion operation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The inversion (for given $x\in \mathbb {F} _{q}$ find $y\in \mathbb {F} _{q}$ such that $xy=1$ ) is one to two orders of magnitude slower than multiplication.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] However, points on a curve can be represented in different coordinate systems which do not require an inversion operation to add two points.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Note that there may be different naming conventions, for example, IEEE P1363-2000 standard uses "projective coordinates" to refer to what is commonly called Jacobian coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] An additional speed-up is possible if mixed coordinates are used.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The speed-up here is a practical rather than theoretical one, and derives from the fact that the moduli of numbers against numbers near powers of two can be performed efficiently by computers operating on binary numbers with bitwise operations.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The curves over $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ with pseudo-Mersenne P-256 and P-384 are recommended by NIST in SP 800-186.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The NIST curves also use *a* = −3, which improves addition in Jacobian coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Bernstein and Lange have criticized some design choices of the NIST curves and list alternative criteria for curve selection in the SafeCurves project.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Other widely deployed curves also use primes with special forms that allow efficient reduction, such as $p=2^{255}-19$ for Curve25519 and $2^{448}-2^{224}-1$ for Curve448.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Unlike most other discrete logarithm problem (DLP) systems (where it is possible to use the same procedure for squaring and multiplication), the EC addition is significantly different for doubling (*P* = *Q*) and general addition (*P* ≠ *Q*) depending on the coordinate system used.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Consequently, it is important to counteract side-channel attacks (e.g., timing or simple/differential power analysis attacks) using, for example, fixed pattern window (a.k.a. comb) methods (note that this does not increase computation time).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Alternatively one can use an Edwards curve; this is a special family of elliptic curves for which doubling and addition can be done with the same operation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Another concern for ECC-systems is the danger of fault attacks, especially when running on smart cards.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Cryptographic experts have expressed concerns that the National Security Agency has inserted a kleptographic backdoor into at least one elliptic curve-based pseudo random generator.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Internal memos leaked by former NSA contractor Edward Snowden suggest that the NSA put a backdoor in the Dual EC DRBG standard.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] One analysis of the possible backdoor concluded that an adversary in possession of the algorithm's secret key could obtain encryption keys given only 32 bytes of PRNG output.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] The SafeCurves project catalogs curves that are easy to implement securely and are designed in a fully publicly verifiable way to minimize the chance of a backdoor.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Shor's algorithm can be used to break elliptic curve cryptography by computing discrete logarithms on a sufficiently large fault-tolerant quantum computer.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Published quantum resource estimates for breaking a curve with a 256-bit modulus (128-bit security level) include 2330 logical qubits and 126 billion Toffoli gates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] For the binary elliptic curve case, 906 logical qubits are necessary to break 128 bits of security.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] These estimates do not imply that current quantum computers can break deployed ECC systems, but they are a reason for migration planning.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In August 2024, NIST approved the first three Federal Information Processing Standards for post-quantum cryptography: FIPS 203 for ML-KEM, FIPS 204 for ML-DSA, and FIPS 205 for SLH-DSA.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NIST describes these standards as principal post-quantum standards for key establishment and digital signatures.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] NSA's CNSA 2.0 guidance similarly identifies quantum-resistant algorithms for national security systems and states that CNSA 1.0 compliance remains required during the transition.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] Supersingular Isogeny Diffie–Hellman Key Exchange was proposed as a post-quantum form of elliptic-curve-based key exchange using isogenies.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] However, new classical attacks undermined the security of this protocol.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In August 2015, the NSA announced that it planned to transition "in the not distant future" to a new cipher suite that is resistant to quantum attacks.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] ECC implementations can be susceptible to invalid-curve attacks if they multiply a secret scalar by attacker-supplied points without verifying that the points lie on the intended curve and in the correct subgroup.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In such attacks, repeated operations on invalid or small-order points can leak information about the private scalar.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-cryptography] In 2019, an invalid-curve attack against AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization was reported to recover a Platform Diffie–Hellman (PDH) private key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The following example illustrates how a shared key is established.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Suppose Alice wants to establish a shared key with Bob, but the only channel available for them may be eavesdropped by a third party.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Initially, the domain parameters (that is, $(p,a,b,G,n,h)$ in the prime case or $(m,f(x),a,b,G,n,h)$ in the binary case) must be agreed upon.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Also, each party must have a key pair suitable for elliptic curve cryptography, consisting of a private key d (a randomly selected integer in the interval $[1,n-1]$ ) and a public key represented by a point Q (where $Q=d\cdot G$ , that is, the result of adding G to itself d times).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Each party must know the other party's public key prior to execution of the protocol.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The shared secret is $x_{k}$ (the *x* coordinate of the point).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Most standardized protocols based on ECDH derive a symmetric key from $x_{k}$ using some hash-based key derivation function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The only information about her key that Alice initially exposes is her public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] So, no party except Alice can determine Alice's private key (Alice of course knows it by having selected it), unless that party can solve the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] No party other than Alice or Bob can compute the shared secret, unless that party can solve the elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman problem.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The public keys are either static (and trusted, say via a certificate) or ephemeral (also known as **ECDHE**, where final 'E' stands for "ephemeral").
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Ephemeral keys are temporary and not necessarily authenticated, so if authentication is desired, authenticity assurances must be obtained by other means.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Authentication is necessary to avoid man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] If one of either Alice's or Bob's public keys is static, then man-in-the-middle attacks are thwarted.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Static public keys provide neither forward secrecy nor key-compromise impersonation resilience, among other advanced security properties.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Holders of static private keys should validate the other public key, and should apply a secure key derivation function to the raw Diffie–Hellman shared secret to avoid leaking information about the static private key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] For schemes with other security properties, see MQV.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] If Alice maliciously chooses invalid curve points for her key and Bob does not validate that Alice's points are part of the selected group, she can collect enough residues of Bob's key to derive his private key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Several TLS libraries were found to be vulnerable to this attack.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The shared secret is uniformly distributed on a subset of $[0,p)$ of size $(n+1)/2$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] For this reason, the secret should not be used directly as a symmetric key, but it can be used as entropy for a key derivation function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The Montgomery form elliptic curve $E_{M,A,B}$ is the set of all $(x,y)\in F_{p}\times F_{p}$ satisfying the equation $By^{2}=x(x^{2}+Ax+1)$ along with the point at infinity denoted as $\infty$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] This is called the affine form of the curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Under a suitably defined addition operation, $E_{M,A,B}(F_{p})$ is a group with $\infty$ as the identity element.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] It is known that the order of this group is a multiple of 4.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] In fact, it is usually possible to obtain A and B such that the order of $E_{M,A,B}$ is $4q$ for a prime q .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] For more extensive discussions of Montgomery curves and their arithmetic one may follow.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] For computational efficiency, it is preferable to work with projective coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Bernstein introduced the map $x_{0}$ as follows: $x_{0}(X:Z)=XZ^{p-2}$ which is defined for all values of X and Z in $F_{p}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Following Miller, Montgomery and Bernstein, the Diffie-Hellman key agreement can be carried out on a Montgomery curve as follows.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Let Q be a generator of a prime order subgroup of $E_{M,A,B}(F_{p})$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Alice chooses a secret key s and has public key $x_{0}(sQ)$ ; Bob chooses a secret key t and has public key $x_{0}(tQ)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The shared secret key of Alice and Bob is $x_{0}(stQ)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Using classical computers, the best known method of obtaining $x_{0}(stQ)$ from $Q,x_{0}(sQ)$ and $x_{0}(tQ)$ requires about $O(p^{1/2})$ time using the Pollards rho algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The most famous example of Montgomery curve is Curve25519 which was introduced by Bernstein.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] The other Montgomery curve which is part of TLS 1.3 is Curve448 which was introduced by Hamburg.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Couple of Montgomery curves named M[4698] and M[4058] competitive to Curve25519 and Curve448 respectively have been proposed in.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] At 256-bit security level, three Montgomery curves named M[996558], M[952902] and M[1504058] have been proposed in.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-diffie-hellman] Apart from these two, other proposals of Montgomery curves can be found at.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] In cryptography, the **Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm** (**ECDSA**) offers a variant of the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA) which uses elliptic-curve cryptography.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] As with elliptic-curve cryptography in general, the bit size of the private key believed to be needed for ECDSA is about twice the size of the security level, in bits.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] For example, at a security level of 80 bits—meaning an attacker requires a maximum of about $2^{80}$ operations to find the private key—the size of an ECDSA private key would be 160 bits.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] On the other hand, the signature size is the same for both DSA and ECDSA: approximately $4t$ bits, where t is the exponent in the formula $2^{t}$ , that is, about 320 bits for a security level of 80 bits, which is equivalent to $2^{80}$ operations.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Suppose Alice wants to send a signed message to Bob.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Initially, they must agree on the curve parameters $({\textrm {CURVE}},G,n)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] In addition to the field and equation of the curve, we need G , a base point of prime order on the curve; n is the additive order of the point G .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The order n of the base point G **must be prime**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Indeed, we assume that every nonzero element of the ring $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ is invertible, so that $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ must be a field.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Alice creates a key pair, consisting of a private key integer $d_{A}$ , randomly selected in the interval $[1,n-1]$ ; and a public key curve point $Q_{A}=d_{A}\times G$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] We use $\times$ to denote elliptic curve point multiplication by a scalar.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Let z be the $L_{n}$ leftmost bits of e , where $L_{n}$ is the bit length of the group order n .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Select a **cryptographically secure random** integer k from $[1,n-1]$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] As the standard notes, it is not only required for k to be secret, but it is also crucial to select different k for different signatures.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] This implementation failure was used, for example, to extract the signing key used for the PlayStation 3 gaming-console.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Another way ECDSA signature may leak private keys is when k is generated by a faulty random number generator.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Such a failure in random number generation caused users of Android Bitcoin Wallet to lose their funds in August 2013.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] To ensure that k is unique for each message, one may bypass random number generation completely and generate deterministic signatures by deriving k from both the message and the private key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] For Bob to authenticate Alice's signature $r,s$ on a message m , he must have a copy of her public-key curve point $Q_{A}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Calculate $e={\textrm {HASH}}(m)$ , where HASH is the same function used in the signature generation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Let z be the $L_{n}$ leftmost bits of e.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The signature is valid if $r\equiv x_{1}{\pmod {n}}$ , invalid otherwise.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Note that an efficient implementation would compute inverse $s^{-1}\,{\bmod {\,}}n$ only once.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Also, using Shamir's trick, a sum of two scalar multiplications $u_{1}\times G+u_{2}\times Q_{A}$ can be calculated faster than two scalar multiplications done independently.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] It is not immediately obvious why verification even functions correctly.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] From the definition of r, this is verification step 6.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] This shows only that a correctly signed message will verify correctly; other properties such as incorrectly signed messages failing to verify correctly and resistance to cryptanalytic attacks are required for a secure signature algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] (provided $x_{1}$ is not too large for the field of the curve) and $y_{1}$ is a value such that the curve equation is satisfied.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Note that there may be several curve points satisfying these conditions, and each different R value results in a distinct recovered key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The signature is valid if $Q_{A}$ , matches Alice's public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The signature is invalid if all the possible R points have been tried and none match Alice's public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] Note that an invalid signature, or a signature from a different message, will result in the recovery of an incorrect public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The recovery algorithm can only be used to check validity of a signature if the signer's public key (or its hash) is known beforehand.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] From the definition of $Q_{A}=d_{A}\times G$ , this is Alice's public key.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] This shows that a correctly signed message will recover the correct public key, provided additional information was shared to uniquely calculate curve point $R=(x_{1},y_{1})$ from signature value r.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] In December 2010, a group calling itself *fail0verflow* announced the recovery of the ECDSA private key used by Sony to sign software for the PlayStation 3 game console.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] However, this attack only worked because Sony did not properly implement the algorithm, because k was static instead of random.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] As pointed out in the Signature generation algorithm section above, this makes $d_{A}$ solvable, rendering the entire algorithm useless.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] On March 29, 2011, two researchers published an IACR paper demonstrating that it is possible to retrieve a TLS private key of a server using OpenSSL that authenticates with Elliptic Curves DSA over a binary field via a timing attack.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] The vulnerability was fixed in OpenSSL 1.0.0f.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] In August 2013, it was revealed that bugs in some implementations of the Java class SecureRandom sometimes generated collisions in the k value.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] This allowed hackers to recover private keys giving them the same control over bitcoin transactions as legitimate keys' owners had, using the same exploit that was used to reveal the PS3 signing key on some Android app implementations, which use Java and rely on ECDSA to authenticate transactions.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] This issue can be prevented by deterministic generation of k, as described by RFC 6979.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve-digital-signature-algorithm] *Technical concerns*: the difficulty of properly implementing the standard, its slowness, and design flaws which reduce security in insufficiently defensive implementations.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In mathematics, an **elliptic curve** is a smooth, projective, algebraic curve of genus one, on which there is a specified point O.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is defined over a field K and describes points in *K*2, the Cartesian product of K with itself.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The curve is required to be non-singular, which means that the curve has no cusps or self-intersections.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] (This is equivalent to the condition 4*a*3 + 27*b*2 ≠ 0, that is, being square-free in x.) It is usually understood that the curve is embedded in the projective plane, with the point O being the unique point at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Many sources define an elliptic curve to be simply a curve given by an equation of this form.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is an abelian variety – that is, it has a group law defined algebraically, with respect to which it is an abelian group – and O serves as the identity element.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If *y*2 = *P*(*x*), where P is any polynomial of degree three in x with no repeated roots, the solution set is a nonsingular plane curve of genus one, an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If P has degree four and is square-free this equation again describes a plane curve of genus one; however, it has no natural choice of identity element.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] More generally, any algebraic curve of genus one, for example the intersection of two quadric surfaces embedded in three-dimensional projective space, is called an elliptic curve, provided that it is equipped with a marked point to act as the identity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Using the theory of elliptic functions, it can be shown that elliptic curves defined over the complex numbers correspond to embeddings of the torus into the complex projective plane.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The torus is also an abelian group, and this correspondence is also a group isomorphism.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves are especially important in number theory, and constitute a major area of current research; for example, they were used in Andrew Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] They also find applications in elliptic curve cryptography (ECC) and integer factorization.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] An elliptic curve is *not* an ellipse in the sense of a projective conic, which has genus zero: see elliptic integral for the origin of the term.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] However, there is a natural representation of real elliptic curves with shape invariant *j* ≥ 1 as ellipses in the hyperbolic plane $\mathbb {H} ^{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Specifically, the intersections of the Minkowski hyperboloid with quadric surfaces characterized by a certain constant-angle property produce the Steiner ellipses in $\mathbb {H} ^{2}$ (generated by orientation-preserving collineations).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Here, the vertex of the hyperboloid serves as the identity on each trajectory curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Topologically, a complex elliptic curve is a torus, while a complex ellipse is a sphere.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Although the formal definition of an elliptic curve requires some background in algebraic geometry, it is possible to describe some features of elliptic curves over the real numbers using only introductory algebra and geometry.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] after a linear change of variables (a and b are real numbers).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This type of equation is called a *Weierstrass normal form*, *Weierstrass form*, or *Weierstrass equation*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The definition of elliptic curve also requires that the curve be non-singular.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Geometrically, this means that the graph has no cusps, self-intersections, or isolated points.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] (see J-invariant#Algebraic_definition for the derivation).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Although the factor −16 is irrelevant to whether or not the curve is non-singular, this definition of the discriminant is useful in a more advanced study of elliptic curves.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The real graph of a non-singular curve has *two* components if its discriminant is positive, and *one* component if it is negative.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For example, in the graphs shown in figure to the right, the discriminant in the first case is 64, and in the second case is −368.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This resulting equation is defined on the whole projective plane, and the curve it defines projects onto the elliptic curve of interest.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] To find its intersection with the line at infinity, we can just posit $Z=0$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This implies $X^{3}=0$ , which in a field means $X=0$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Y on the other hand can take any value, and thus all triplets $(0,Y,0)$ satisfy the equation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In projective geometry this set is simply the point $O=[0:1:0]$ , which is thus the unique intersection of the curve with the line at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Since the curve is symmetric about the x axis, given any point P, we can take −*P* to be the point opposite it.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] We then have $-O=O$ , as O lies on the XZ plane, so that $-O$ is also the symmetrical of O about the origin, and thus represents the same projective point.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If P and Q are two points on the curve, then we can uniquely describe a third point *P* + *Q* in the following way.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] First, draw the line that intersects P and Q.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This will generally intersect the cubic at a third point, R.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] We then take *P* + *Q* to be −*R*, the point opposite R.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This definition for addition works except in a few special cases related to the point at infinity and intersection multiplicity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The first is when one of the points is O.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Here, we define *P* + *O* = *P* = *O* + *P*, making O the identity of the group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If *P* = *Q*, we only have one point, thus we cannot define the line between them.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In this case, we use the tangent line to the curve at this point as our line.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In most cases, the tangent will intersect a second point R, and we can take its opposite.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If P and Q are opposites of each other, we define *P* + *Q* = *O*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Lastly, if P is an inflection point (a point where the concavity of the curve changes), we take R to be P itself, and *P* + *P* is simply the point opposite itself, i.e. itself.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Let K be a field over which the curve is defined (that is, the coefficients of the defining equation or equations of the curve are in K) and denote the curve by E.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Then the K-rational points of E are the points on E whose coordinates all lie in K, including the point at infinity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The set of K-rational points is denoted by *E*(*K*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] *E*(*K*) is a group, because properties of polynomial equations show that if P is in *E*(*K*), then −*P* is also in *E*(*K*), and if two of P, Q, R are in *E*(*K*), then so is the third.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Additionally, if K is a subfield of L, then *E*(*K*) is a subgroup of *E*(*L*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The above groups can be described algebraically as well as geometrically.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Given the curve *y*2 = *x*3 + *bx* + *c* over the field K (whose characteristic we assume to be neither 2 nor 3), and points *P* = (*xP*, *yP*) and *Q* = (*xQ*, *yQ*) on the curve, assume first that *xP* ≠ *xQ* (case *1*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The line equation and the curve equation intersect at the points xP, xQ, and xR, so the equations have identical y values at these values.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] and because both equations are cubics, they must be the same polynomial up to a scalar.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] and this is an element of K, because s is.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If *xP* = *xQ*, then there are two options: if *yP* = −*yQ* (case *3*), including the case where *yP* = *yQ* = 0 (case *4*), then the sum is defined as 0; thus, the inverse of each point on the curve is found by reflecting it across the x axis.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The slope is given by the tangent to the curve at (*x**P*, *y**P*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For a general cubic curve not in Weierstrass normal form, we can still define a group structure by designating one of its nine inflection points as the identity O.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In the projective plane, each line will intersect a cubic at three points when accounting for multiplicity.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For a point P, −*P* is defined as the unique third point on the line passing through O and P.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Then, for any P and Q, *P* + *Q* is defined as −*R* where R is the unique third point on the line containing P and Q.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For an example of the group law over a non-Weierstrass curve, see Hessian curves.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] A curve *E* defined over the field of rational numbers is also defined over the field of real numbers.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Therefore, the law of addition (of points with real coordinates) by the tangent and secant method can be applied to *E*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The explicit formulae show that the sum of two points *P* and *Q* with rational coordinates has again rational coordinates, since the line joining *P* and *Q* has rational coefficients.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This way, one shows that the set of rational points of *E* forms a subgroup of the group of real points of *E*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This section is concerned with points *P* = (*x*, *y*) of *E* such that *x* is an integer.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Rational points can be constructed by the method of tangents and secants detailed above, starting with a *finite* number of rational points.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] More precisely the Mordell–Weil theorem states that the group *E*(**Q**) is a finitely generated (abelian) group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] By the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups it is therefore a finite direct sum of copies of **Z** and finite cyclic groups.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The proof of the theorem involves two parts.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The first part shows that for any integer *m* > 1, the quotient group *E*(**Q**)/*mE*(**Q**) is finite (this is the weak Mordell–Weil theorem).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Second, introducing a height function *h* on the rational points *E*(**Q**) defined by *h*(*P*0) = 0 and *h*(*P*) = log max(|*p*|, |*q*|) if *P* (unequal to the point at infinity *P*0) has as abscissa the rational number *x* = *p*/*q* (with coprime *p* and *q*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This height function *h* has the property that *h*(*mP*) grows roughly like the square of *m*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Moreover, only finitely many rational points with height smaller than any constant exist on *E*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The theorem however doesn't provide a method to determine any representatives of *E*(**Q**)/*mE*(**Q**).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The rank of *E*(**Q**) is the number of copies of **Z** in *E*(**Q**) or, equivalently, the number of independent points of infinite order.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture is concerned with determining the rank.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] One conjectures that it can be arbitrarily large, even if only examples with relatively small rank are known.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It has rank 20, found by Noam Elkies and Zev Klagsbrun in 2020.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Curves of rank higher than 20 have been known since 1994, with lower bounds on their ranks ranging from 21 to 29, but their exact ranks are not known and in particular it is not proven which of them have higher rank than the others or which is the true "current champion".
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Moreover, elliptic curves whose Mordell–Weil groups over **Q** have the same torsion groups belong to a parametrized family.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture (BSD) is one of the Millennium problems of the Clay Mathematics Institute.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The conjecture relies on analytic and arithmetic objects defined by the elliptic curve in question.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] At the analytic side, an important ingredient is a function of a complex variable, *L*, the Hasse–Weil zeta function of *E* over **Q**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This function is a variant of the Riemann zeta function and Dirichlet L-functions.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It is defined as an Euler product, with one factor for every prime number *p*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The zeta function of an elliptic curve over a finite field **F***p* is, in some sense, a generating function assembling the information of the number of points of *E* with values in the finite field extensions **F***pn* of **F***p*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] where the 'trace of Frobenius' term $a_{p}$ is defined to be the difference between the 'expected' number $p+1$ and the number of points on the elliptic curve E over $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ , viz.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] We may define the same quantities and functions over an arbitrary finite field of characteristic p , with $q=p^{n}$ replacing p everywhere.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The L-function of *E* over **Q** is then defined by collecting this information together, for all primes *p*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] where *N* is the conductor of *E*, i.e. the product of primes with bad reduction $(\Delta (E\mod p)=0$ ), in which case *ap* is defined differently from the method above: see Silverman (1986) below.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This product converges for Re(*s*) > 3/2 only.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Hasse's conjecture affirms that the *L*-function admits an analytic continuation to the whole complex plane and satisfies a functional equation relating, for any *s*, *L*(*E*, *s*) to *L*(*E*, 2 − *s*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In 1999 this was shown to be a consequence of the proof of the Shimura–Taniyama–Weil conjecture, which asserts that every elliptic curve over *Q* is a modular curve, which implies that its *L*-function is the *L*-function of a modular form whose analytic continuation is known.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] One can therefore speak about the values of *L*(*E*, *s*) at any complex number *s*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The *Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture* relates the arithmetic of the curve to the behaviour of this *L*-function at *s* = 1.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It affirms that the vanishing order of the *L*-function at *s* = 1 equals the rank of *E* and predicts the leading term of the Laurent series of *L*(*E*, *s*) at that point in terms of several quantities attached to the elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Let *K* = **F***q* be the finite field with *q* elements and *E* an elliptic curve defined over *K*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In other words, the number of points on the curve grows proportionally to the number of elements in the field.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This fact can be understood and proven with the help of some general theory; see local zeta function and étale cohomology for example.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The set of points *E*(**F***q*) is a finite abelian group.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It is always cyclic or the product of two cyclic groups.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] over **F**71 has 72 points (71 affine points including (0,0) and one point at infinity) over this field, whose group structure is given by **Z**/2**Z** × **Z**/36**Z**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The number of points on a specific curve can be computed with Schoof's algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] where the field *Kn* is the (unique up to isomorphism) extension of *K* = **F***q* of degree *n* (that is, $K_{n}=F_{q^{n}}$ ).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The zeta function is a rational function in *T*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The Sato–Tate conjecture is a statement about how the error term $2{\sqrt {q}}$ in Hasse's theorem varies with the different primes *q*, if an elliptic curve E over **Q** is reduced modulo q.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It was proven (for almost all such curves) in 2006 due to the results of Taylor, Harris and Shepherd-Barron, and says that the error terms are equidistributed.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves over finite fields are notably applied in cryptography and for the factorization of large integers.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] These algorithms often make use of the group structure on the points of *E*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Algorithms that are applicable to general groups, for example the group of invertible elements in finite fields, **F****q*, can thus be applied to the group of points on an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For example, the discrete logarithm is such an algorithm.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The interest in this is that choosing an elliptic curve allows for more flexibility than choosing *q* (and thus the group of units in **F***q*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Also, the group structure of elliptic curves is generally more complicated.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves can be defined over any field *K*; the formal definition of an elliptic curve is a non-singular projective algebraic curve over *K* with genus 1 and endowed with a distinguished point defined over *K*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Here *p* and *q* are elements of *K* such that the right hand side polynomial *x*3 − *px* − *q* does not have any double roots.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] for arbitrary constants *b*2, *b*4, *b*6 such that the polynomial on the right-hand side has distinct roots (the notation is chosen for historical reasons).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] provided that the variety it defines is non-singular.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If characteristic were not an obstruction, each equation would reduce to the previous ones by a suitable linear change of variables.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] One typically takes the curve to be the set of all points (*x*,*y*) which satisfy the above equation and such that both *x* and *y* are elements of the algebraic closure of *K*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Points of the curve whose coordinates both belong to *K* are called ***K*-rational points**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Many of the preceding results remain valid when the field of definition of *E* is a number field *K*, that is to say, a finite field extension of **Q**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] In particular, the group *E(K)* of *K*-rational points of an elliptic curve *E* defined over *K* is finitely generated, which generalizes the Mordell–Weil theorem above.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] A theorem due to Loïc Merel shows that for a given integer *d*, there are (up to isomorphism) only finitely many groups that can occur as the torsion groups of *E*(*K*) for an elliptic curve defined over a number field *K* of degree *d*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] More precisely, there is a number *B*(*d*) such that for any elliptic curve *E* defined over a number field *K* of degree *d*, any torsion point of *E*(*K*) is of order less than *B*(*d*).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] As for the integral points, Siegel's theorem generalizes to the following: Let *E* be an elliptic curve defined over a number field *K*, *x* and *y* the Weierstrass coordinates.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Then there are only finitely many points of *E(K)* whose *x*-coordinate is in the ring of integers *O**K*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The properties of the Hasse–Weil zeta function and the Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture can also be extended to this more general situation.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The formulation of elliptic curves as the embedding of a torus in the complex projective plane follows naturally from a curious property of Weierstrass's elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Here, *g*2 and *g*3 are constants; ℘(*z*) is the Weierstrass elliptic function and ℘′(*z*) its derivative.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It should be clear that this relation is in the form of an elliptic curve (over the complex numbers).
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The Weierstrass functions are doubly periodic; that is, they are periodic with respect to a lattice Λ; in essence, the Weierstrass functions are naturally defined on a torus *T* = **C**/Λ.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] This map is a group isomorphism of the torus (considered with its natural group structure) with the chord-and-tangent group law on the cubic curve which is the image of this map.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] It is also an isomorphism of Riemann surfaces from the torus to the cubic curve, so topologically, an elliptic curve is a torus.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] If the lattice Λ is related by multiplication by a non-zero complex number c to a lattice *c*Λ, then the corresponding curves are isomorphic.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Isomorphism classes of elliptic curves are specified by the j-invariant.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The isomorphism classes can be understood in a simpler way as well.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] The constants *g*2 and *g*3, called the modular invariants, are uniquely determined by the lattice, that is, by the structure of the torus.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] However, all real polynomials factorize completely into linear factors over the complex numbers, since the field of complex numbers is the algebraic closure of the reals.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] with j-invariant *j*(*τ*) and *λ*(*τ*) is sometimes called the modular lambda function.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] For example, let *τ* = 2*i*, then *λ*(2*i*) = (−1 + √2)4 which implies *g*′2, *g*′3, and therefore *g*′23 − 27*g*′32 of the formula above are all algebraic numbers if τ involves an imaginary quadratic field.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Note that the uniformization theorem implies that every compact Riemann surface of genus one can be represented as a torus.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] for integers a and b in the range 0 ≤ (*a*, *b*) < *n*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] M(*w*, *z*) is the arithmetic–geometric mean of w and z.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] At each step of the arithmetic–geometric mean iteration, the signs of zn arising from the ambiguity of geometric mean iterations are chosen such that |*wn* − *zn*| ≤ |*wn* + *zn*| where wn and zn denote the individual arithmetic mean and geometric mean iterations of w and z, respectively.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Over the complex numbers, every elliptic curve has nine inflection points.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Every line through two of these points also passes through a third inflection point; the nine points and 12 lines formed in this way form a realization of the Hesse configuration.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] where $\operatorname {Div} ^{0}$ is the group of divisors of degree 0.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Elliptic curves over finite fields are used in some cryptographic applications as well as for integer factorization.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/elliptic-curve] Typically, the general idea in these applications is that a known algorithm which makes use of certain finite groups is rewritten to use the groups of rational points of elliptic curves.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] In mathematics, the **Montgomery curve** is a form of elliptic curve introduced by Peter L.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Montgomery in 1987, different from the usual Weierstrass form.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] It is used for certain computations, and in particular in different cryptography applications.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Generally this curve is considered over a finite field *K* (for example, over a finite field of *q* elements, *K* = **F***q*) with characteristic different from 2 and with *A* ≠ ±2 and *B* ≠ 0.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Over such fields, the group order of the curve is always divisible by 4.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Montgomery curves are also considered over the rationals with the same restrictions for *A* and *B*.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Every Montgomery curve has a point at $(0,0)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] It is possible to do some "operations" between the points of an elliptic curve: "adding" two points $P,Q$ consists of finding a third one R such that $R=P+Q$ ; "doubling" a point consists of computing $[2]P=P+P$ (For more information about operations see The group law) and below.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] A point $P=(x,y)$ on the elliptic curve in the Montgomery form $By^{2}=x^{3}+Ax^{2}+x$ can be represented in Montgomery coordinates $P=(X:Z)$ , where $P=(X:Z)$ are projective coordinates and $x=X/Z$ for $Z\neq 0$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Notice that this kind of representation for a point loses information: indeed, in this case, there is no distinction between the affine points $(x,y)$ and $(x,-y)$ because they are both given by the point $(X:Z)$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] However, with this representation it is possible to obtain multiples of points, that is, given $P=(X:Z)$ , to compute $[n]P=(X_{n}:Z_{n})$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] The first operation considered above (addition) has a time-cost of 3**M**+2**S**, where **M** denotes the multiplication between two general elements of the field on which the elliptic curve is defined, while **S** denotes squaring of a general element of the field.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] The second operation (doubling) has a time-cost of 2**M** + 2**S** + 1**D**, where **D** denotes the multiplication of a general element by a constant; notice that the constant is $(A+2)/4$ , so A can be chosen in order to have a small **D**.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] The following algorithm represents a doubling of a point $P_{1}=(X_{1}:Z_{1})$ on an elliptic curve in the Montgomery form.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] The cost of this implementation is 1M + 2S + 1*A + 3add + 1*4.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Here M denotes the multiplications required, S indicates the squarings, and a refers to the multiplication by A.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] As it has been observed before, this equation has three solutions that correspond to the $~x$ coordinates of $P_{1}$ , $P_{2}$ and $P_{3}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] 4) To find the $~y$ coordinate of the point $P_{3}$ it is sufficient to substitute the value $x_{3}$ in the line $~y=lx+m$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Notice that this will not give the point $P_{3}$ directly.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Indeed, with this method one find the coordinates of the point $~R$ such that $R+P_{1}+P_{2}=P_{\infty }$ , but if one needs the resulting point of the sum between $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ , then it is necessary to observe that: $R+P_{1}+P_{2}=P_{\infty }$ if and only if $-R=P_{1}+P_{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] So, given the point $~R$ , it is necessary to find $~-R$ , but this can be done easily by changing the sign to the $~y$ coordinate of $~R$ .
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] In other words, it will be necessary to change the sign of the $~y$ coordinate obtained by substituting the value $x_{3}$ in the equation of the line.
[src:elliptic-curve-cryptography/montgomery-curve] Let K be a field with characteristic different from 2.
